# Error Handling Standards

## No empty catch blocks

```ts
// Bad — silently swallows errors
try {
  await riskyOperation();
} catch {}

// Bad — hides the error
try {
  await riskyOperation();
} catch (e) {
  return '';
}

// Good
try {
  await riskyOperation();
} catch (err) {
  logger.error('riskyOperation failed', { err, context });
  throw err; // or handle explicitly
}
```

## Don't swallow errors in streaming/concurrent operations

When using `Promise.allSettled` or batch operations, always check and surface rejected items:

```ts
const results = await Promise.allSettled(items.map(process));
const failures = results.filter(r => r.status === 'rejected');
if (failures.length > 0) {
  logger.error('Batch had failures', { count: failures.length, failures });
}
```

## Explicit error types at boundaries

At service/Lambda boundaries, map unknown errors to typed errors before propagating:

```ts
// Bad
throw new Error('something went wrong');

// Good
throw new ConsentUpdateError('userId not found', { userId, partition });
```

## No re-throwing without context

If you catch and rethrow, add context:

```ts
// Bad
} catch (err) { throw err; }

// Good
} catch (err) {
  throw new Error(`Failed to upsert consent for userId=${userId}`, { cause: err });
}
```

## Validate at system boundaries only

Don't add defensive null checks inside internal functions where the type system guarantees non-null. Do validate at:
- API/Lambda entry points (external input)
- DynamoDB query results (external data)
- Parsed configuration values
